<a name="Mapping_Tools"></a><h2>Mapping Tools</h2>
<p>Currently there are only two tools that can be used for mapping with Doom 3.
</p>
<ul><li><a href="/web/20070729231147/http://www.qeradiant.com/" class='external text' title="http://www.qeradiant.com/">GTKradiant</a>
</li><li><a href="/web/20070729231147/http://modwiki.net/wiki/DoomEdit" title="DoomEdit">DoomEdit</a> (built-in)
</li></ul>
<p>DoomEdit can be started by typing "editor" in Doom 3's console or by starting Doom 3 with "+editor" in the shortcut's target command parameters.
</p>
<a name="General_Mapping_Concepts"></a><h2>General Mapping Concepts</h2>
<p>Check out <a href="/web/20070729231147/http://modwiki.net/wiki/Maps_%28folder%29" title="Maps (folder)">mapping filetypes</a> for that info.
</p>
<a name="The_Void"></a><h3>The Void</h3>
<p>Mapping for Doom 3 and other id games is based on a filling principle ('additive' editing).
</p><p>Every new map starts as an empty space known as "The Void" which you fill with brushes and entities.
</p>
<a name="Brushes"></a><h3>Brushes</h3>
<p>Brushes are the shapes that form map geometry. Floors, ceilings, walls, ect... are all created with brushes. Brushes are convex structures. All brushes that don't belong to a specific user-created entity are placed in the <i>Worldspawn</i> entity.
</p>
<a name="Entities"></a><h3>Entities</h3>
<p>Entities are the actors and objects you place in your map. Lights, monsters, items, doors, ect... are all examples of entities. 
</p>
<a name="Patches"></a><h3>Patches</h3>
<p>Patches are a way to manipulate and add complex surfaces to your map.
</p><p>These are used to create convex and, more importantly, concave features within your map. 
</p><p>Any number of organic structures can be created using a patch (curves, arches, pillars etc...).
</p><p>Unlike brushes, patches don't seal the level from "the void" so you must enclose them with brushes (usually with the caulk <a href="/web/20070729231147/http://modwiki.net/wiki/Material_%28decl%29" title="Material (decl)"> material</a>).
</p>
<a name="The_Worldspawn"></a><h3>The Worldspawn</h3>
<p>The Worldspawn is an entity that exists in every map. It's purpose is to act as a container for every static brush in your map.
</p>
<a name="Common_Problems"></a><h2>Common Problems</h2>
<a name="Leaks"></a><h3>Leaks</h3>
<p>Leaks occur when the playing area of the map or the origin of an entity is exposed to the void.
</p>
<a name="Finding_Leaks"></a><h4>Finding Leaks</h4>
<p>Whenever you compile a map and a leak occurs information about that leak is stored in the pointfile.
</p><p>You can view this information by selecting File > <a href="/web/20070729231147/http://modwiki.net/wiki/Pointfile" title="Pointfile"> Pointfile</a> in the level editor immediately after a failed compile.
</p><p>The editor will draw a red line connecting an entity to empty space. You should travel along the line until you find the hole in your level and seal it.
</p>
<a name="Non-Vis_Blocking_Materials"></a><h4>Non-Vis Blocking Materials</h4>
<p>Some materials in the material browser are non-solid or transparent. These materials do not seal the map and upon compile the engine will report a leak.
</p><p>A material's corresponding <a href="/web/20070729231147/http://modwiki.net/wiki/Material_%28decl%29" title="Material (decl)"> material shader</a> can yield clues as to why a certain texture will not seal the map. If the Pointfile seems to go through a solid piece of geometry check that surface's material to see if the problem lies there.
</p>
<a name="Testing"></a><h2>Testing</h2>
<p>To test a map properly there are serveral cvars that can be set or toggled to give you visual information about you map.
</p>
<a name="Lighting"></a><h4>Lighting</h4>
<p>bind &lt;key&gt; "toggle r_showLightCount 0 1 2"
</p><p><a href="/web/20070729231147/http://modwiki.net/wiki/R_showLightCount_%28cvar%29" title="R showLightCount (cvar)"> r_showlightcount</a> 1 (# of lights on a single triangle)
<br />black - 0
<br />red - 1
<br />green - 2
<br />dark blue - 3
<br />cyan - 4
<br />purple - 5
<br />white - 6+
</p><p>r_showlightcount 2 (same except includes overdraw of any surfaces behind the nearest one)  
</p><p>It can also help to set r_showtris 1 and r_showlightscissors 1 
bind &lt;key&gt; "toggle r_showLightCount 0 1; toggle r_showtris 0 1;toggle r_showlightscissors 0 1"
</p>
<a name="Geometry"></a><h4>Geometry</h4>
<p>bind &lt;key&gt; "toggle r_showtris 0 1 2 3"
</p>
<a name="VisPortals"></a><h4>VisPortals</h4>
<p>bind &lt;key&gt; "toggle r_showTris 0 2;toggle r_useScissor 0 1;toggle r_showPortals 0 1"
Best explaination of visportals and these cvars is <a href="/web/20070729231147/http://www.iddevnet.com/doom3/visportals.php" class='external text' title="http://www.iddevnet.com/doom3/visportals.php">here</a>.
</p>
<a name="Overall"></a><h4>Overall</h4>
<p>bind &lt;key&gt; "toggle com_showfps"
</p><p><a href="/web/20070729231147/http://modwiki.net/wiki/Com_showFPS_%28cvar%29" title="Com showFPS (cvar)"> com_showfps</a> 
<br />This toggles the display of the Frames Per Second.
</p><div class="printfooter">
